LAURIE MARKER: Well, we don't
know because they're extinct.

00:50:19.840 --> 00:50:21.430
We are trying to
find out much more

00:50:21.430 --> 00:50:25.350
about some of these
extinct populations

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:30.920
by collecting, like,
samples from the museums.

00:50:30.920 --> 00:50:35.420
So they are all so
similar that it's

00:50:35.420 --> 00:50:38.880
hard to actually see that much
differentiation with them.

00:50:38.880 --> 00:50:40.850
But it would be an animal
that would probably

00:50:40.850 --> 00:50:48.381
be much more similar to
that the Iranian cheetah,

00:50:48.381 --> 00:50:49.130
the Asian cheetah.

00:50:51.404 --> 00:50:53.320
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
there are about 10,000

00:50:53.320 --> 00:50:54.420
in the wild right now.

00:50:54.420 --> 00:50:58.060
I'm wondering what a healthy and
sustainable population would be

00:50:58.060 --> 00:51:02.440
or if you have a target
number in mind for that?

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:09.120
LAURIE MARKER: I
kind of like 100,000.

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:12.190
That's not that
many, necessarily,

00:51:12.190 --> 00:51:14.620
throughout the continent.

00:51:14.620 --> 00:51:16.980
Then if you kind of look
at-- I do a lot of math

00:51:16.980 --> 00:51:18.390
and I do a lot of modeling.

00:51:18.390 --> 00:51:21.450
You'd have to then look at, if
you need-- and I know so much.

00:51:21.450 --> 00:51:23.410
So I'm always figuring
out how much land

00:51:23.410 --> 00:51:25.050
they'd need, how
much prey they'd

00:51:25.050 --> 00:51:27.629
need, how much
grasslands they'd need,

00:51:27.629 --> 00:51:30.170
how many cattle are out there,
how many people are out there.

00:51:30.170 --> 00:51:34.210
How do we actually switch that
back into these grasslands

00:51:34.210 --> 00:51:36.120
where we've got
wildlife and prey?

00:51:36.120 --> 00:51:38.530
The people are actually
getting a different livelihood

00:51:38.530 --> 00:51:42.540
than being poor,
starving farmers.

00:51:42.540 --> 00:51:45.780
And all the sudden, the people
are doing something different.

00:51:45.780 --> 00:51:48.270
And yet the wildlife
is still maintaining

00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:49.960
these grassland systems.

00:51:49.960 --> 00:51:53.460
Where you then have elephants
and rhinos in the land.

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:55.720
You know, we're looking at
this kind of big support

00:51:55.720 --> 00:51:57.550
system for a big continent.

00:51:57.550 --> 00:51:59.610
And the wildlife are
a support system,

00:51:59.610 --> 00:52:02.700
it's part of biodiversity.

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:06.600
I'd be real happy if we
could double the population

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:10.560
in the next five
years or 10 years.

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:13.980
We've doubled the population
in Namibia in 20 years

00:52:13.980 --> 00:52:16.160
and we're kind of
stabilizing it.

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:18.690
But with that, we now
need to, I guess--

00:52:18.690 --> 00:52:20.790
and we are-- working
with the other countries

00:52:20.790 --> 00:52:22.730
throughout the
cheetah's range in order

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:26.270
to help stabilize those
and grow those populations.

00:52:26.270 --> 00:52:29.050
But it's all about people.

00:52:29.050 --> 00:52:31.610
And so I just keep
trying to figure out

00:52:31.610 --> 00:52:34.740
ways of helping people.

00:52:34.740 --> 00:52:37.130
And wanting them all
to love the cheetah.

00:52:37.130 --> 00:52:39.750
I mean, wasn't he beautiful?

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:42.610
I know it's not--
I bet you haven't

00:52:42.610 --> 00:52:45.070
had a cheetah at Google before.

00:52:45.070 --> 00:52:46.580
And on Earth Day.

00:52:46.580 --> 00:52:51.630
It's a celebration of
Earth Day, 44 years.

00:52:51.630 --> 00:52:53.635
And think you.

00:52:53.635 --> 00:52:56.520
You all can do an awful
lot to just spread the word

00:52:56.520 --> 00:53:00.940
and get more people
involved in many ways.

00:53:00.940 --> 00:53:04.120
And I'm always happy to
answer more questions.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:06.350
And welcome all of you
to come down and visit.

00:53:06.350 --> 00:53:09.770
Oh, I could, I'd be happy
to sign books as well.

00:53:09.770 --> 00:53:12.220
Buy books, buy books.

00:53:12.220 --> 00:53:15.720
You can also adopt cheetahs
online, or adopt a dog,

00:53:15.720 --> 00:53:16.780
at our website.

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:19.610
We've got a really nice
website so please go to it.

00:53:19.610 --> 00:53:20.940
Cheetah.org.

00:53:20.940 --> 00:53:23.180
If you have kids in
school here and you

00:53:23.180 --> 00:53:25.500
want to have the
Dicelys come and bring

00:53:25.500 --> 00:53:28.750
one of their educational
programs, they're just amazing.

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:31.470
And they help support
many of us who

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:36.110
have cat conservation
programs worldwide.

00:53:36.110 --> 00:53:38.680
But I live in an area
where-- Namibia's got

00:53:38.680 --> 00:53:41.260
like 2.2 million people.

00:53:41.260 --> 00:53:46.140
And that's not very many
in a very large country.

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:50.360
However, that's why-- we got
lots of thorn bushes-- getting

00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:52.940
to know people when I
come over here from Africa

00:53:52.940 --> 00:53:53.830
is really nice.

00:53:53.830 --> 00:53:56.610
And I hope that you'll all
become part of our family

00:53:56.610 --> 00:54:00.060
and let us know who
you are and learn ways

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:01.490
that you can
actually get involved

00:54:01.490 --> 00:54:06.287
in making the world different
and better with cheetahs.

00:54:06.287 --> 00:54:08.328
So, thank you.

